<subsection xml:id="subsec-expressing-probability-outcomes-in-fractions-in-different-situations">
    <title>Expressing probability outcomes in fractions in different situations</title>
    <p>
        Expressing probability outcomes in fractions means representing the likelihood of an event happening as a fraction, where the numerator represents the number of desired outcomes and the denominator represents the total number of possible outcomes.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key points about expressing probability as fractions:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Structure: A probability fraction is written as "favorable outcomes / total possible outcomes". 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Interpretation: The larger the numerator, the higher the probability of the desired event happening. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Range: Probabilities expressed as fractions always fall between 0 (impossible event) and 1 (certain event). 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <activity>
        <p>
            Work in groups
        </p>
        <p>
            In a bag, there are <m>10</m> marbles of different colors:
        </p>
        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>4</m> red marbles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>3</m> blue marbles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>2</m> green marbles
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>1</m> yellow marble
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p>
            A student picks one marble at random from the bag.
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Identify the total number of possible outcomes.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Find number of times you pick a marble, probability of picking each color, express it as a fraction and fill in your results in the table below
                    </p>
                    <table>
                        <title>Identifying the Total Number of Possible Outcomes</title>
                        <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                            <row halign="left" header="yes">
                                <cell>Colour</cell>
                                <cell>Number of Marbles</cell>
                                <cell>Number of Times Picked</cell>
                                <cell>Probability (Fraction Form)</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row halign="left" header="yes">
                                <cell>Red</cell>
                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row halign="left" header="yes">
                                <cell>Blue</cell>
                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row halign="left" header="yes"> 
                                <cell>Green</cell>
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row halign="left" header="yes">
                                <cell>Yellow</cell>
                                <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </table>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss your results with other groups.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        Learning points
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Probability of an event is the likelihood of an event occurring.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Probability as a measure can be expressed as a fraction.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Akinyi tossed a fair coin <m>20</m> times and noted the result of each flip. She recorded whether the coin landed on heads or tails for every trial.
            </p>
            <p>
                The results of her experiments are shown in the table below.
            </p>
            <table>
                <title></title>
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row halign="left" header="yes">
                        <cell>Face</cell>
                        <cell>Head(H)</cell>
                        <cell>Tail(T)</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row halign="left" header="yes">
                        <cell>Number of times</cell>
                        <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>12</m></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <p>
                Find the probability of getting a;
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Head
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Tail
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Total trials = <m>8+12 = 20</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           P(Head) = Number of heads/Total trials.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            P(H) = <m>\frac{8}{20}</m> = <m>\frac{2}{5}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            P(Tail) = Number of tails/Total trials.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            P(T) = <m>\frac{12}{20}</m> = <m>\frac{3}{5}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Mr. Indimuli puts <m>30</m> letters in a bag. The letters include <m>8</m>F's, <m>7</m>D's, <m>6</m>C's, <m>5</m>B's and <m>4</m>A's. He will randomly select a letter out of the bag to determine your semester grade. Find the following probabilities. Give an answer as a fraction.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the probability of getting an F.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the probability of passing.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate the probability of getting an A or B.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Total numbers of letters: <m>8+7+6+5+4 = 30</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate P(F): Number of F's/Total number of letters.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Number of <m>\textbf{F's} = 8</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            P(F) = <m>\frac{8}{30}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Probability of passing: P(A,B,C,D).
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Number of A's = <m>4</m>, B's = <m>5</m> , C's = <m>6</m>, D's = <m>7</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total for A,B,C,D = <m>4+5+6+7 = 22</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            P(A,B,C,D) = <m>\frac{22}{30}</m> = <m>\frac{11}{15}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            To calculate P(A,B):
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Total for A and B ; <m>4+5 = 9</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            P(A,B) = <m>\frac{9}{30}</m> = <m>\frac{3}{10}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
</subsection>